ON Friday, their shacks were washed away by raging floodwaters that left them homeless. TodayÂ  (Sunday) they went to their damaged shacks to salvage the little they can get. Others managed to get some things but others came back with nothing. The water from the nearby stream was still raging but atleast not as much as before.Residents from Riverside squatter camp said they had been given three days to sleep at the local church but they don't know where will they go afterward. A number of shacks were swept away last Friday after flash floods hit Ivory Park. About 180 people were displaced after their shacks were swept away. One man was confirmed dead. Residents told Daily Sun that the victim was trying to save his fridge when he swept away. Residents who stay nearby the stream said they have been staying there for more than three years and they have never seen anything like that.Community leader Tumi Legau said lack of jobs and inability to pay rent let them to staying there. "We appeal to the government to give us proper land and we will build for ourselves," said Legau. Residents say the situation is bad and they feel like they have been dumped to die of hunger. "We have since been waiting for food but nothing is coming. On Saturday Joburg Mayor Dr Mpho Phalatse visited the area and promised residents that she would engage with the housing department from Monday. Resident Lever Chauke said they hoped that she would keep her promise. "We are in need of a place to stay because the church will be evicting us soon and where will we go. We have lost everything," said Chauke. Most residents escaped with their lives but they have lost valuables such as IDs, birth certificates and other personal documents.